Next, let us look at what level a double is Responsive Double.|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


nt||

%%b5
ST||MD|2,,,|sv|o|rh||ah|Responsive Double|AH|Board 5|NT|^B@2
Most experts play Responsive Doubles up to the 4-level, typically 4@D. Therefore, in this auction,|mb|1dx4dx|an|Responsive Double|at| the double is a Responsive Double.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT|^B@2
On the other hand, Larry Cohen says, "As with all doubles, there is no upper limit. If the opponents bid and raise to a high level, you can be sure they have lots of trumps. It makes no sense to define double as Penalty." If it bidding goes as |UB|4|mb|1sx4sx|at| is shown now,|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


NT|^B@2
or if it is like|UB|4|MB|1s2h4sx|at| the one you see now.|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


NT|^B@2
The the doubles by you are Responsive Doubles - as high as 4@S.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||AT|
^B@2^*BMM: ^*NHowever, It is possible that Mr. Cohen has modified his style since he wrote the piece on Responsive Double - note the last 2 quizzes. Next, Mr. Schutzman will clarify the issue. Also he has additional explanation for the Responsive Double.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BSchutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Let me clarify what Larry Cohen means when he says doubles at the 4-level are responsive. Most experts play all doubles of 4 level bids are "value showing". They are neither pure penalty nor pure takeout. They say, "Partner, I have some values and this hand belongs to us. Do something intelligent. |
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BSchutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Pass if you think we are beating it and we have no better spot. Bid if you have the distribution and values such that you think it is better if we play the hand." |
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BSchutzman: ^*N|cp||at|It is not always easy for partner to decide what to do (which is why the opponents preempted in the first place), but that does not change the meaning of the double.|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BSchutzman: ^*N|cp||at|On related topic, the Responsive Doubles presented here are what most people play -- that is they only occur when partner makes a bid and the opponents bid and raise. |
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BSchutzman: ^*N|cp||at|However, a few people play that Responsive Doubles are on whenever there are 2 remaining unbid suits. In particular, this can happen when partner makes a takeout double. Thus, in the auction 1@C-x-1@S-x, you can play that the 2nd double is still Responsive because hearts and diamonds are both unbid. |
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BSchutzman: ^*N|cp||at|However, 1C-1D-1S-x is not responsive, since only hearts are unbid (although some people still play that the double in that auction does show hearts with a weakish hand; I do not.)|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


NT||

